\begin{proof} It is clear that ${\mathcal GRS}_k({\bf a},{\bf v},\infty)$ is a $q$-ary $[n+1,k]$-linear code. Thus, it is sufficient to show that for every nonzero polynomial $f(x)$, the codeword ${\bf c}:=(f({\alpha}_1),f({\alpha}_2),\dots,f({\alpha}_n),f_{k-1})$ has Hamming weight at least $n+2-k$. If $\deg(f(x))<k-1$, then $f(x)$ has at most $k-2$ roots, thus $f(x)$ has at most $k-2$ zeros at $\{{\alpha}_1,{\alpha}_2,\dots,{\alpha}_n\}$. This implies that the  codeword ${\bf c}$ has Hamming weight at least $n-k+2$. If $\deg(f(x))=k-1$, then $f(x)$ has at most $k-1$ zeros at $\{{\alpha}_1,{\alpha}_2,\dots,{\alpha}_n\}$. In addition, the last coordinate of ${\bf c}$ is $f_{k-1}\neq0$  in this case. Therefore, the Hamming weight of ${\bf c}$ is at least $n-k+1+1=n-k+2$. The proof is completed.
\end{proof}
